      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(discord): extend component callback ttl",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Raise the default Discord component callback registry TTL from 30 minutes to 7 days.\n- Expand the bounded `agentComponents.ttlMs` override maximum from 24 hours to 30 days.\n- Refresh Discord config docs, UI hints, generated config metadata, and baseline hashes.\n- Add registry-level coverage proving the default remains usable until the 7-day boundary and expires afterward.\n\nThis keeps asynchronous review and approval cards usable by default while preserving an explicit bounded override for deployments that need a different lifetime. Intentionally out of scope: changing component authorization, reusable-component semantics, or Discord interaction handling outside registry TTLs.\n\nReviewers should focus on the default/max TTL choice and whether the stale-callback tradeoff is acceptable.\n\n## Linked context\n\nCloses #90390\n\nRelated #84184 and #84189, which added the configurable TTL field while preserving the old 30-minute default.\n\n## Retention and safety notes\n\n- Durable callback state remains count-bounded: persistent component and modal namespaces each open with `maxEntries: 500` plus the default TTL.\n- The plugin state store sweeps expired rows and evicts oldest live rows above `maxEntries` on register, so the longer TTL does not make persistent registry storage unbounded.\n- On high-volume servers, the 500-entry cap can become the effective lifetime bound before the 7-day TTL. That is an existing count-bound behavior and may be worth revisiting separately if maintainers want a different capacity tradeoff.\n- The process-local in-memory registry is not the durable retention boundary, and this PR does not change its semantics.\n- Component authorization and `allowedUsers` checks are unchanged. Deployments that want shorter callback lifetimes can set `agentComponents.ttlMs`.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- Behavior or issue addressed: Discord component callbacks without an explicit `agentComponents.ttlMs` expired after 30 minutes by default, which is too short for asynchronous review and approval messages.\n- Real environment tested: OpenClaw source checkout with a standalone registry invocation, Discord registry/config/send tests, generated config metadata checks, and changed-lane type/lint checks. No live Discord multi-day click was performed.\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch:\n\n```sh\nnode --import tsx --input-type=module\n```\n\nThe command imported `extensions/discord/src/components-registry.ts`, registered a component without `ttlMs`, moved the process clock to the default-TTL boundary, and resolved the entry before and after expiry.\n\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output):\n\nTerminal output from the standalone registry invocation:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"source\": \"extensions/discord/src/components-registry.ts\",\n  \"registeredWithoutTtlMs\": true,\n  \"defaultTtlMs\": 604800000,\n  \"resolvesAtSevenDaysMinusOneMs\": true,\n  \"resolvesAtSevenDaysPlusOneMs\": false,\n  \"observedExpiresAtDeltaMs\": 604800000\n}\n```\n\n- Observed result after fix: the real registry module keeps an entry registered without `ttlMs` resolvable until just before the 7-day boundary and stops resolving it just after that boundary. The focused Discord test run also passed 3 files and 67 tests.\n- What was not tested: live Discord button clicks over a multi-day wall-clock interval.\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints: the live interval is intentionally not attempted in this small PR; the standalone registry invocation and registry clock-boundary test cover the expiry logic deterministically, and send-path tests continue to cover configured TTL propagation.\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged): current main defined `DEFAULT_COMPONENT_TTL_MS = 30 * 60 * 1000`, documented default `1800000`, and capped `agentComponents.ttlMs` at `86400000`.\n\n## Tests and validation\n\nCommands run after this patch:\n\n- `pnpm test extensions/discord/src/components.test.ts extensions/discord/src/config-schema.test.ts extensions/discord/src/send.components.test.ts -- --reporter=verbose`\n- `pnpm config:channels:check`\n- `pnpm config:docs:check`\n- `pnpm check:changelog-attributions`\n- `git diff --check`\n- `pnpm tsgo:extensions`\n- `pnpm tsgo:extensions:test`\n- `pnpm lint:extensions`\n- `pnpm tsgo:core`\n- `pnpm tsgo:core:test`\n- `pnpm lint:core`\n- `pnpm check:no-conflict-markers`\n\nRegression coverage added or updated:\n\n- Added a default registry TTL boundary test in `extensions/discord/src/components.test.ts`.\n- Updated Discord config schema tests for the new 30-day maximum and max+1 rejection.\n- Regenerated channel config metadata and config docs baseline hash.\n\n## Risk checklist\n\nDid user-visible behavior change? (`Yes`)\n\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? (`Yes`)\n\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? (`Yes: stale callback lifetime increases; auth, secrets, network, and tool execution behavior are unchanged`)\n\nHighest-risk area: longer-lived Discord component callbacks can keep old messages actionable for longer.\n\nMitigation: `allowedUsers` and component authorization semantics are unchanged; deployments can lower `agentComponents.ttlMs`; persistent registry state remains bounded by `maxEntries`; the schema still enforces a finite maximum, now 30 days.\n\n## Current review state\n\nNext action: maintainer review, CI, and explicit maintainer decision on the 7-day default plus 30-day maximum.\n\nBot/reviewer comments addressed:\n\n- Removed the release-owned `CHANGELOG.md` edit.\n- Added source-level retention-bound documentation at the persistent Discord component/modal stores.\n- Added the retention-bound explanation and latest validation evidence to this PR body.\n\nStill waiting on: maintainer acceptance or revision of the TTL policy.\n",
